<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910604-0061</DOCNO><DOCID>910604-0061.</DOCID><HL>   New England Broker   Is Sentenced to Jail,   Assessed $10,000 Fine</HL><DATE>06/04/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C21</SO><IN>SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENT (RGU)</IN><NS>SECURITIES REGULATION (RGU)</NS><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)</GV><LP>   BOSTON -- Charles H. Howard III, a onetime prominent NewEngland stockbroker, was fined $10,000 and sentenced to ayear and a day in prison for conspiring to obstruct aSecurities and Exchange Commission investigation into allegedinsider trading in New England thrift stocks.   Mr. Howard, 45 years old, pleaded guilty to one count ofconspiracy last month in federal court. He faced a maximum offive years in prison and $250,000 fine. But he received apenalty almost identical to that of Robert C. DiGennaro, theformer chairman of Suffield Savings Bank in Suffield, Conn.,with whom he conspired to obstruct the SEC investigation.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. DiGennaro was fined $4,000 and sentenced to one yearin prison after pleading guilty to a charge of conspiracy.   As a former director and vice president of defunct ThomsonMcKinnon Securities Inc., Mr. Howard was a high-profileplayer in the trading of small New England bank stocks duringthe hot market in mid-1980s.   The SEC investigation focused on possible improper tradingin connection with a Suffield Savings announcement in 1987that it would acquire Coastal Savings Bank of Portland,Maine. The SEC also looked into allegations of insidertrading of other New England bank stocks.</TEXT></DOC>